1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
🔹 What is Parliament?

The Parliament of India is the supreme legislative body.

It consists of:

1️⃣ President
2️⃣ Lok Sabha (Lower House)
3️⃣ Rajya Sabha (Upper House)

📌 Mentioned in Article 79

🔵 Lok Sabha (House of the People)
Key Features:
Maximum strength: 552
Elected directly by people
Term: 5 years
Can be dissolved
Important Roles:
Makes laws
Controls executive
Passes budget
No-confidence motion

📌 Speaker presides over Lok Sabha.

🔴 Rajya Sabha (Council of States)
Key Features:
Maximum strength: 250
Permanent house (not dissolved)
Members elected by State Assemblies
Term: 6 years
1/3 members retire every 2 years

📌 Vice President is Chairman.

🔹 Functions of Parliament
1️⃣ Legislative Functions
Makes laws on Union & Concurrent List
2️⃣ Financial Functions
Passes budget
Controls taxation

📌 Money Bill can be introduced only in Lok Sabha.

3️⃣ Executive Control
Questions, debates, motions
No-confidence motion
4️⃣ Electoral Functions
Participates in election of President & VP
5️⃣ Constitutional Functions
Amends Constitution (Article 368)
🔹 Important Points
Lok Sabha is more powerful in financial matters
Rajya Sabha represents states
Parliament ensures accountability of government
